Lagos – Dimeji Lawal, former Super Eagles midfielder, has charged the Nigeria Football Federation (NFF) to expedite actions and name a substantive coach for the national team. The diminutive player who spoke to DAILY INDEPENDENT ahead of the two friendly matches lined up for the former African champions against Mexico and Ecuador, saying it was high time the football house named a substantive manager for the national team in view of the fact that the 2023 Africa Cup of Nations (AFCON) qualifiers are around the corner. “We should not just assume that we have it against the opponents in our group for the 2023 Africa Cup of Nations (AFCON) qualifiers. -Advertisement- “I was thinking that before now, they would have finalized issues relating to this new coach. It is not even good that we don’t have a new coach for these friendly matches. “These games (friendly matches) should have been for the coach to study the players before the qualifiers and that we are still dragging this issue is not good,” he said. Nigeria will be confronting the trio of Sierra Leone, Guinea Bissau and Sao Tome and Principe in Group A of the qualifiers for a place in next year’s Africa Cup of Nations (AFCON) in Cote d’Ivoire. Meanwhile, against Ecuador and Mexico, the NFF has given the interim coach, Salisu Yusuf, the go-ahead to name players for the matches and prosecute them while he also to be held sway pending the naming of a substantive manager for the team.